{"/service/ndnp/gu/batch_gu_ara_ver01/data/sn89053204/00393344350/1907101101/0439.xml":{"full_text":"AMERICUS TIMES'RECORDER\ntwenty-ninth year\nIF YOU\u2019RE WAITING\nSchaffner\ncloJies. Copyright 1907 by Hart Schaffner Marx\nW. D BAILEY.\nOutfitter for Men and Boys\nForxyth Next t n Po-toffice Anirricus Ga.\nS\\\\ J J if\nHair Brushes. I\nTooth Brushes.\nCloth Brushes.\nShoe Brushes.\nBath Brushes. g\nNail Brushes.\nCamplexion Brushes.\nWe Have Them.\nThe quality and prices\nare the right thing.\nREMBERT\u2019S\nDRUG STORE i\n113 FORSYTE ST.\nP\nWHEN READY TO BUILD\nWhether a Mansion, a Store or Cottage, see\nJOHN W. SHIVER\nWHEN READY TO PAINT\nShiver Has the Goods, the Best goods and\nLargest \u25a0'toek.\nEverthiug in\u2019 t Lumber, Mantles, Grates and, in -fact, all that goe\nin a house. Buying Paints in Carload Lots, His prices are the Lowes\nwhere quality counts. Mills and street, (Phone 117\nAMERICUS, GEORGIA, FRIDAY MORNING OCTOBER 11, 1907\nSTATE FAIR OPENS\nWITH 600 D CROWDS\nTwo Co iventions Close La\nbors and Adjourn.\nATLANTA, GA., October 10.\u2014\n(Special.)\u2014The Georgia State Fair\nopened its gates this morning with a\nlarge crowd in attendance. The dis\nplays and amusement features were\nthe best in years. The day was offi\ncially designated as Boilermakers\u2019\nand Spinners\u2019 Day. Saturday, Octo\nber 19, will be the big day, when Wil\nliam Jennings Bryan will be the at\ntraction. Next Wednesday will be\nFarmers\u2019 Union Day. The Fair will\nclose October 26.\nThe American Association of Boil\nermakers at today's session discuss\ned the labor situation and came to\nthe conclusion that it was the duty\nof manufacturers to unite against un\njust encroachments of the labor or\nganizations, declaring that it was a\ncase of \"fighting fire with fire.\u201d It\nwas decided to hold the next annual\nmeeting in Atlantic City. The con\nvention closed with a banquet at\nnight.\nFourth Assistant Postmaster-Gen\neral LeGraw addressed the conven\ntion of rural letter carriers today.\nAmong other things he said that\nPostmaster General Meyer would rec\nommend the establishment of pos\ntal savings banks paying 2 per cent,\ninterest. In the afternoon the dele\ngates were treated to a barbecue at\nTucker, Ga., given by President Un\nsay at his home. In the afternoon a\nbusiness session was held, an ad\njournment sine die being taken at\n10 o\u2019clock at night.\nAUSTRIAN EMPEROR\nDISREGARDS DOCTOR\nVIENNA, October 10.\u2014(Special.)\nThe condition of Emperor Francis\nJoseph is improved but the aged mon\narch still refuses to cease work as\nrecommended by his physicians, al\nthough suffering from fever and bron\nchitis. His physicians are apprehen\nsive of serious results.\nSOUTHERNERS HISS\nATLANTA RECTOR\nRICHMOND, VA\u201e October 10.\u2014\nC. B. Wilmer, of Atlanta, rector of\nSt. Luke\u2019s Episcopal church, was\nhissed at today\u2019s session of the Epis\ncopal convention. His offense was\ndefending the Bishop of Michigan in\nadvocating the appointment of ne\ngro bishops. The question was up\nyesterday, but was not settled. That\nit is a live issue was evident.\nThe House of Bishops yesterday\nvoted down the motion of the Bishop\nof Albany providing for more strin\ngent canons on the subject of mar\nriage and divorce. After discussion\nit was decided to make no changes\nalong this line at present.\nCHICAGO \\viNS~\nTHIRD GAME\nCHICAGO, ILL., October 10.\u2014\n(Special.)\u2014Chicago this afternoon\ndefeated Detroit to the tune of 5 to\n1. This was the third of the World\u2019s\nchampionship series, the first being\na tie, the second and third going to\nChicago.\nThe batteries in today's game were:\nChicago, Reulbach and King; Detroit,\nKillian and Schmidt.\nMUSICAL RECITAL\nTHIS EVENING\nMiss Annie Mae Bell will hold her\nmonthly recital at her studio tonight\nat eight o\u2019clock. The excellence of\nher pupils\u2019 work is well known and\nwill insure a large audience. The\npublic is cordially invited.\nUNFINISHED\n35 YEARS\nPHILADELPHIA, October 10.\u2014\nThe City Hall is to he completed af\nter standing unfinished for 35 years.\nPlans have been drawn by City\nArchitect Powell and estimates have\nbeen invited from builders.\n\u201cA hard chill, pain through the chest, difficult\ncr% \u00a5J breathing.\u201d If this should be your experience,\nI! SDO /T/QK 7/send for your doctor. It may be pneumonia!\nJL UU A To doctor yourself would be too risky. Ifyour\np doctor cannot come at once, give Ayer\u2019s\nf Ash your doctor If he does not think It Che Pectoral When he comes, tell him\nWould be wise for you to keep Ct bottle j... J.O.AyerCo.,\n|of Ayer' 3 Cherry Pectoral in the house, exactly what y OU Lowai^JMw^\nFIRST TO4ST ON\n\u201cCITY Os SAVANNAH\"\nGraceful Tribute Paid By\nGeneral Manager.\nSAVANNAH, GA., October 10.\u2014\n(Special)\u2014At the first dinner aboard\nthe Steamship \u2018\u2018City of Savanah,\u201d en\nroute from New York to Savannah,\nGeneral Manager Pleasants proposed\nthe following graceful toast:\n\"The City of Savannah, the ship\nand that beautiful and prosperous\ncity in Georgia, which we soon shall\nsee. To those of you that are not\nfamiliar with the South, its cherished j\ntraditions and strong characteristics, j\n1 want to tell you and ask you to tell\nthe world that Savannah exemplifies\nall that is good of the past and all\nthat leads to a brilliant future.\n\"In these troublesome times when\nstates and municipalities seem over\nwrought and perplexed with wrongs,\nfancied or true, which they attribute\nto the evils of corporate influences,\nit is unique to see a thriving, busy\ncity, the largest cotton port on the\nAtlantic coast, a market whose daily\nquotations establish the value of\nnaval stores for the entire world, uni\nting with a transportation company\nt to give you a sincere welcome, for\nSavanah believes, and strives to\nteach all that come within her bor\nders to believe, that her public utili\nties, he they they on land or sea, are\nesential to her prosperity, and in aid\ning them she helps herself to a ma\nterial and permanent advancement.\nAnd in this spirit I ask you to drink\nto the \u201cCity of Savanah.\u2019\nMARRIAGE WAS A\nROMANTIC ONE\nMr. and Mrs. C. E. Hopkins, whose\nromantic marriage was solemnized\nhere the evening previous, left yes\nterday morning for Dawson and will\nsoon go to New Orleans, the home of\nthe fortunate groom. Mr. Hopkins\ntravels for a Savannah house, while\nhis pretty bride, Miss Ethel M. Mel\nton, resided in San Francisco. The\ncouple met in Amerieus, doubtless by\nappointment, and repairing to the\nresidence of Dr. J. P. Wardlaw, of\nFirst Methodist church, they were\nsoon united in marriage. Mr. Hop\nkins travels for Ludden Bates of\nSavanah, and is well known in sou\nthern Georgia. Several friends here\nextended congratulations and best\nwishes when informed of his ro\nmantic marriage (in Amerieus.\nGUARDS\u2019 BATTALION\nLEAVES SERVICE\nSAVANNAH, GA., October 10.\u2014\n(Special)\u2014Declining further service\nunder the Dick bill, the Vounteer\nGuards Batalion Heavy Artillery, Maj.\nW. B. Stevens commanding, last night\nvoted to severe its connection with\nthe state troops, and will exist as\nan independent organization. The\nGuards constitute one of the most\nimportant of Savannah\u2019s military\nbodies and the example set may be\ncommunicated to other troops, as\nall feel the burdens of the new regu\nlations.\nSTRICKEN DOWN\nWITH APPENDICITIS\nMr. Belknap Carswell, a young man\nemployed by the Davenport Drug\nCompany, was stricken down with\nappendicitis on Wednesday. An op\neration was recommended but was\ndeferred to see it if could not be\navoided. The young man is quite\npopular with a large circle of ac\nquaintances who will regret to hear\nof his illness.\nSEASON A LATE ONE\nAT THE THEATER\nIt will yet be well nigh a month\nbefore Amerieus play-goers will see i\nanything in the line theatrical. The\nseason is the latest ever known\u2014and I\nthere were no early bookings for I\nAmerieus. The nearest attraction at\npresent Is dated for November 7th,\nthen there will come ten or a\ndozen closely bunched. There are\nseveral good attractions booked, hut\nthey are a long time in the future.\nNew York\u2019s Most Advanced\nStylse In Men\u2019s Fall Suits\nand Overgarments\nAjj Ljgff\nFORM FOURTEEN\neopvmoHT, iso?\nThe FECHHEiMERFISHELCO.\n'cc \u00a5ORK\nHawes\u2019 Famous and Popular Hats, $3.00.\n\u201cEclipse\u201d Shirts, World\u2019s Best, SI.OO and $1.50\nFaucy Vests, Fancy Sox, Beautiful Line.\nUnderwear, Neckwear, Gloves Suspenders.\nWe are headquarters and will save you dollars on every\nthing you may need in above lines and will greatly appreciate\nan opportunity to show you through whether you buy or not\nCHAS. L. ANSLEY.\nLOOKS FOR LOWER\nPRICE IN COT FON\nThinks Values Will Decline\nto 9 Cents.\nMr. Crawford Wheatley returned to\nAmericus yesterday ::i New York,\nwhere he spent tv.o or three weeks\nrecently on busings and In recreation.\nWhile there Mr. Wheatley was in\nWall street a good deal and upon\nthe Cotton Exhange, and says that\nthe sentiment among cotton men in\nthe metropolis is decidely \u201cbearish.\u201d\nThis is due in great part to the gen\neral financial stringency in the East\nand the outlook, from that stand\npoint, cf a big cotton crop. Money\nis so tight there that the large bank\ning houses are compelled to decline\nmaking advances to their customers\nin Texas and the Southwest, to be\nused for holding purposes. They con\ntend that 11 cents is high for cotton\nand that farmers should sell at cur\nrent rices and thus add to the vol- j\nume of currency by bringing in for\neign capital. Mr. Wheatley says the\nNew York contingent calculate upon\na crop of more than thirteen million\nbales, in which event 9 cents instead\nof It cents will soon be the ruling\nprice. Just one year ago today there\nwas killing frost throughout the cot- j\nton belt, which r.<-nt prices upward,\nbut th \u2022ml balmy weather,'\nit is contended, will add an ext.r:i\nquarter million bales each week to\nthe general crop if it keeps up for\nany length of time, as now* seems pro\nbable. It is in reality \u201ccotton mak\ning weather.\u201d.\nBUSINESS OUTLOOK\nIS EXCELLENT\n\u201cOctober has been an exceedingly\ngood month, and the outlook for busi\nness the next two months is better\nthan 1 have ever known it,\u201d said\nMr. W. E. Hamilton, the Lamar street\nmerchant yesterday. \"I think our\nbusiness men have one of the best\nfalls and winters ahead of them they\nhave ever known. Our county is\nprosperous and the merchants are\nsharing in the prosperity of the pub-\nlie at large.\u201d I\nare all here, and in the identical fabric\npatterns shown by the smart csstom tail\nors of Fifth Avenue. You shouldn\u2019t\nfail to see these splendid specimens of\nhigh class tailoring\u2014 to try on the new\nmodels of your size\u2014for\n\u201cEFF EFF\u201d\nFashionable Clothes\nrepresent the best there is in materials\nand workmanship, while our pricer are\nnot higher than you would pay for an\nordinary ready-to-wear.\nCome see our superb collection of\n\u201cEFF-EFF\u201d\nFall Suits at slsto S4O\nRain coats and overcoats $lO to $35.\nOdd Trousers, Paragon make $5.00 to\n$12.50.\nCrawford*s Men\u2019s Shoes, $3.50 and $4.\nLOOKS LIKE THE BEARS\nNOW HAVE THE BULGE\nCotton Values Are Squeezed\nDown Thirty Points.\nYesterday\u2019s bright and balmy wea\nther aroused the bears from inertia\nand brought them stampeding to the\ncotton patch and the open market,\ngiving a fright to the quaking bulls\nand sending them terrified out into\nthe tall wmods.\nIt was \u201cbear day\u201d and the grizzlies\nmade the best of it.\nThey fiercely hammered the mark\net, with the sunbeam for a cudgel,\nand succeeded in putting values down\nthirty points, or more than a quar\nter of a cent.\nLater, there was a slight reaction\non covering and the net loss for the\nday was but twenty points.\nYet this was terrific for the man\nwho still held his bales for 15 cents\ninstead of selling heretofore at cur\nrent prices. But the holding move\nment will soon be on in earnest, and\nnot a few farmers about Americus\nwill hold their bales.\nAfter the slump in values yester\nday, 11 cents was the ruling price\nin the Americus market with 11 1-8\nfor good middling grades.\n\u20141 i\nKNEW A GOOD THING\nWHEN HE USED IT\n\u201cGive me two bottles of \u201cBears\nfoot,\u201d said a man from the country\nto Druggist D. F. Davenport yester\nday afternoon.\nAs the druggist was wrapping the\npackage for him the purchaser vol\nunteered the information:\n\u201cI have been using Bearsfoot in\nmy family for some years. It's the\nfinest tonic and blood purifier I ever\ncame across. I would not be without\nit for anything.\u201d\nBearsfoot is steadily forging to the\nfront,\u2019 said Mr. Davenport after the\ncustomer had left. \u201cIt has been on\nthe market a number of years, and\nwithout any great pushing it has\nwon its way into the public confi\ndence and each year\u2019s sales show a\ndecided increase.\u201d\nNUMBER 240","height":"29532","width":"19870"}}
